Yes, it *is* nice that folks are beginning to be more, uh, mellow at this site.  A little respect, tolerance and kindness goes a long way.  And it's nice to see The Doc back.  Really.<br><br>
To Doc Del- I'm sorry, but I just don't agree with you that &quot;the general population at large&quot; mistreated Vietnam Vets during the war and beyond the war years.  As I've said before, there were protestors who spat, called names, etc. And I'm sure there are still people who may see VVets as baby killers, rapists, whatever.  But in the last 35 years I've never met any of 'em.  I find it very hard to believe that those kind of people were not a small minority. Of course, I don't know how you define &quot;mistreatment.&quot;  I guess the thing I find sad, although I certainly understand it, is how many vets who post here assume *all* protestors spat, called names, etc.  That, I think, is like a protestor assuming all VVets raped someone while they were in Vietnam. Both perceptions are ridiculous, IMHO.<br><br>
To Doc Spatz- I don't think the protest movement was an Avoid The Draft movement.  <br><br>
To Varanelli- Did you (do you) have as much anger towards the McNamaras, Johnsons, Nixons, Westmorlands, Kennedys, etc., as you have against those who were granted amnesty? If not, why not?<br><br>
 
